    • Method Detail

      • indexDataDef

        public void indexDataDef(cz.melkamar.andruian.ddfparser.model.DataDef dataDef,
                         boolean fullReindex)
        Index data defined by the given DataDef object.

        Build a SPARQL query based on the DataDef and run this query on a data SPARQL controller. The query will select all objects of a type defined in the DataDef and find their linked location objects and position coordinates (via a federated query, those objects may be accessible through a different controller - in the prototype version this will be the RÃšIAN SPARQL controller). The indexing is run asynchronously by delegating the method call to IndexServiceAsyncCall.indexDataDefAsync(DataDef, boolean).

        Parameters:
        dataDef - A definition of the data.
        fullReindex - If true, reindex everything. If false, skip querying of objects already indexed (incremental reindex).

      • getRunningJobs

        public java.util.List<cz.melkamar.andruian.ddfparser.model.DataDef> getRunningJobs()
        Get all indexing jobs that are currently running. A running job is a Future that is present in the indexingJobs collection and does not give any return value (returns null). That means its execution has not ended yet.
        Returns:
        A list of DataDef objects that are currently being indexed.

      • getFinishedJobs

        public java.util.List<IndexService.FinishedJobReport> getFinishedJobs()
        Get all indexing jobs that have finished and have not yet been read. Remove all finished jobs from the pool. Once a job finishes, it stays in the pool and waits to be read, quite like a message in a message queue system.
        Returns:
        A list of IndexService.FinishedJobReport objects describing the result of all finished jobs.

      • getErroredJobs

        public java.util.Map<cz.melkamar.andruian.ddfparser.model.DataDef,java.lang.Exception> getErroredJobs()
        Get all indexing jobs that have finished with an exception. Remove all errored jobs from the pool. Once a job finishes, it stays in the pool and waits to be read, quite like a message in a message queue system.
        Returns:
        A map with DataDef as keys to the Exception that caused the job to fail.

      • reindexAll

        public void reindexAll(boolean fullReindex)
        Reindex all data definitions that are present in the system.
        Parameters:
        fullReindex - If true, drop all existing data before indexing. If false, the indexing is done incrementally. That means that the SPARQL index query will filter out IRIs of all objects that are already indexed.

      • dropData

        public void dropData(java.lang.String dataDefIri)
        Delete all indexed data of the given data definition.
        Parameters:
        dataDefIri - The IRI of the data definition whose data to drop.

      • getIndexedPlacesCount

        public int getIndexedPlacesCount(java.lang.String dataDefIri)
        Get the number of places indexed for the given data definition.
        Parameters:
        dataDefIri - The IRI of the data definition for which to count its data points.
        Returns:
        The number of places belonging to the data definition.

      • addDatadefFile

        public void addDatadefFile(java.lang.String dataDefFileUrl)
                    throws cz.melkamar.andruian.ddfparser.exception.RdfFormatException,
                           java.io.IOException,
                           cz.melkamar.andruian.ddfparser.exception.DataDefFormatException
        Add a new data definition file to the system. The file must be a RDF file in the Turtle format. The file is parsed and all data definitions it contains are added to the system for indexing.
        Parameters:
        dataDefFileUrl - The URL pointing to the RDF file.
        Throws:
        cz.melkamar.andruian.ddfparser.exception.RdfFormatException - When the file cannot be parsed as a RDF file.
        java.io.IOException - General read exception.
        cz.melkamar.andruian.ddfparser.exception.DataDefFormatException - When the file can be parsed as a RDF file, but does not conform to the structure prescribed by the data definition schema.
